<DOC><DOCNO> AP890619-0055 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0909EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan-US 1stLd-Writethru a0501 06-19 0252</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0501,0257</SECOND><HEAD>Guerrillas: American Photographer Arrested in Kabul</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: New throughout to ADD background on O'Brien and previous arrestsof foreigners in Afghanistan. No pickup.</HEAD><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An American free-lance photographertraveling with Moslem guerrillas has been captured and is being heldby the Afghan government, Afghan guerrilla sources said today.   They identified him as Tony O'Brien, 42, a photographer fromSanta Fe, N.M., on assignment for Time-Life Inc. He had beencovering the Afghan war based in the Pakistani frontier city ofPeshawar.   The Afghan government did not immediately confirm the arrest.U.S. Embassy officials in Pakistan refused to comment on the report.   Guerrilla sources in Pakistan who demanded anonymity said O'Brienwas captured Wednesday in western Kabul, the capital. The sourcessaid he was being held in the capital and was reported to be in goodcondition.   At least three Western correspondents and two foreign aid workershave been captured while traveling with the guerrillas during the11-year war in Afghanistan. All of them were later released unharmed.   The report on O`Brien is the first known case of an American'scapture.   The U.S.- and Pakistani-supported guerrillas have been fightingthe Soviet-supported Afghan government for a decade.   Soviet combat troops ended nine years of involvement in the warFeb. 15 but continue to arm the Kabul government.   O'Brien had made several previous forays into Afghanistan withthe guerrillas. His photographs have appeared in several major U.S.publications, including The New York Times and Time magazine.</TEXT></DOC>